[[File:Shree_Sanatan_Dharma_Mandal_temple_(Kampala)_05.JPG|thumb|Shree Sanatan Dharma Mandal temple in [[Kampala]]]] {{Hinduism by country}} [[File:Location Uganda AU Africa.svg|thumb|190px|Uganda]] __NOTOC__ '''Hinduism in [[Uganda]]''' arrived when the colonial [[British Empire]] brought [[Hindu]]s along with other Indian workers to its [[East Africa]]n colonies in late 19th and early 20th centuries.<ref name="MittalThursby2009p87"/><ref name="Knott2016p91">{{cite book|author=Kim Knott|title=Hinduism: A Very Short Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Ts6CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA91 |year=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-874554-9|pages=91–92}}</ref> The largest arrival of Hindu immigrants to Uganda, some educated and skilled but mostly poor and struggling from the famine-prone areas of [[Punjab]] and [[Gujarat]], was to help construct the [[Kenya-Uganda Railway]] connecting landlocked parts of Uganda and Kenya with the port city of [[Mombasa]].<ref name="JonesRyan2006p10"/><ref name="Nyep48">{{cite book|author=Malory Nye|title=A Place for Our Gods: The Construction of an Edinburgh Hindu Temple Community|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QF5cAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA48|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-78504-7|pages=48–50}}</ref> The largest departure of Hindus from Uganda occurred when General [[Idi Amin]] expelled them and seized their properties in 1972.<ref name="JonesRyan2006p10"/><ref name="Nyep48"/><ref name=fick199>{{cite book|author=David S. Fick|title=Entrepreneurship in Africa: A Study of Successes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EL0366oH3ckC&pg=PA199 |year=2002|publisher=Greenwood Publishing|isbn=978-1-56720-536-7|page=199}}</ref>
In addition to building major infrastructure projects, Hindus were a part of a global movement of workers to parts of British [[East Africa]], aimed at helping the British government to establish services, retail markets and administrative support.<ref name="MittalThursby2009p87">{{cite book|author1=Sushil Mittal|author2=Gene Thursby|title=Studying Hinduism: Key Concepts and Methods|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QdBFq2Ia79AC&pg=PA87|year=2009|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-41829-9|pages=87–88}}</ref><ref name="Knott2016p91"/><ref>{{cite book|author1=David Levinson|author2=Karen Christensen|title=Encyclopedia of Community: From the Village to the Virtual World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t1geOjQ6R0MC&pg=PA592|year=2003|publisher=Sage Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-2598-9|page=592}}</ref> The British invited Indian laborers as local skilled labor was unavailable. At the peak of the infrastructure projects in Uganda-Kenya, 32,000 people were brought in from India.<ref name=Wolmar182/> Nearly 2,500 workers died because of difficult and unsafe working conditions during these projects. After the project ended, nearly 70% of the workers returned to India, while some 6,000 were absorbed in railway and other British operations such as retail and administration.<ref name=Wolmar182>{{cite book| last = Wolmar| first = Christian| authorlink = Christian Wolmar| year = 2009| title = Blood, Iron & Gold: How the Railways Transformed the World| location = London| publisher = Atlantic| pages = 182–183}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last1=Otte| first1=T. G.| last2=Neilson| first2=Keith (eds.)| title=Railways and International Politics: Paths of Empire, 1848–1945| series=Military History and Policy| year=2012| publisher=Routledge| location=London| isbn=9780415651318| pages=8–9}}</ref> Those who remained included Hindus, Muslims, Jains and Sikhs. Many from this ethnic group became financially successful.<ref name="JonesRyan2006p10"/>
==Expulsion of Hindus and other Asians by Idi Amin== {{Main|Expulsion of Asians from Uganda}}
[[File:Idi Amin -Archives New Zealand AAWV 23583, KIRK1, 5(B), R23930288.jpg|thumb|140px|left|General [[Idi Amin]] expelled all Hindus and other Asians in 1972 from Uganda. Twenty years later, Uganda reversed that law.]] After colonialism ended, Hindus (along with Jains and Sikhs) were discriminated against in East Africa including Uganda. This was a part of the policies of various East African governments in their promotion of [[Africanization#Africanization of civil services|Africanization]] based on laws and policies under which commercial and professional sectors of the economy had to be owned by indigenous Africans.<ref name="Vertovec2013p87">{{cite book|author=Steven Vertovec|title=The Hindu Diaspora: Comparative Patterns|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jRRUAQAAQBAJ |year=2013|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-136-36712-0|pages=87–89|chapter=Chapter 4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Ndlovu-Gatsheni, Sabelo J.|author2=Ndhlovu, Finex|title=Nationalism and National Projects in Southern Africa: New Critical Reflections |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J90WAgAAQBAJ |year=2013|publisher=Africa Institute of South Africa|isbn=978-0-7983-0395-8|pages=62–74}}</ref> The Hindus, along with Jains, Sikhs, Jews and other religious groups, were affected during this period of xenophobic targeting of Asians and Europeans by African leaders.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ronald Aminzade|title=Race, Nation, and Citizenship in Postcolonial Africa: The Case of Tanzania|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zQ6hAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA89 |year=2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-43605-3|pages=89–90}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=John E. Roemer|author2=Woojin Lee|author3=Karine van der Straeten|title=Racism, Xenophobia, and Distribution: Multi-issue Politics in Advanced Democracies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NbbPdXV4cDoC&pg=PA147|year=2007|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-02495-3|pages=147–148}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Harold G. Coward|author2=John R. Hinnells|author3=Raymond Brady Williams|title=The South Asian Religious Diaspora in Britain, Canada, and the United States |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mXrdXMaaYCkC&pg=PA80 |year=2012|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-9302-1|pages=80–81}}</ref>
When General [[Idi Amin]] came to power by overthrowing an elected government in Uganda, he adopted a policy of religious and ethnic cleansing against people of Asian religions. Himself a Muslim, he announced that he had a dream, where "Allah told him that the Asians, exploiters who did not want to integrate with the Africans, had to go".<ref name="Vassanji2012p25">{{cite book|author=M.G. Vassanji|title=No New Land|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FdCVIo4JrWwC&pg=PA25|year=2012|publisher=McClelland & Stewart|isbn=978-1-55199-707-0|page=25}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=John S. Pobee|title=Religion in a Pluralistic Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5oCws-rwwNwC&pg=PA41|year=1976|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-04556-2|pages=40–41}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=E. Khiddu-Makubuya, Victoria Miriam Mwaka and P. Godfrey Okoth|title=Uganda, thirty years of independence, 1962–1992|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tOEtAQAAIAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Makerere University Press|page=243}}</ref> In 1972, he selectively expelled the Hindus along with other Asians from Uganda, and seized their properties.<ref name="Henckaerts1995p22"/> Most of those expelled were second or third generation Hindus, many with dual Ugandan and British citizenship. While he expelled Hindus and people of other religions with origins in India, Idi Amin did not expel Christians of British or French origins living in Uganda.<ref name="Henckaerts1995p22">{{cite book|author=Jean-Marie Henckaerts|title=Mass Expulsion in Modern International Law and Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s3kaTLyAKo0C|year=1995|publisher=Martinus Nijhoff Publishers|isbn=90-411-0072-5|pages=22–25}}</ref>
According to Kim Knott, professor of Religious and Secular Studies at Lancaster University, there were 65,000 Hindus in Uganda in 1970, but all were expelled by Idi Amin.<ref>{{cite book|author=Kim Knott|title=Hinduism: A Very Short Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kXheCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT114|year=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-106271-1|page=114}}</ref> The expelled Hindus mass migrated to other countries during this period,<ref name="MittalThursby2009p87"/><ref name="JonesRyan2006p10"/> particularly the [[United Kingdom]] (28,000 refugees{{refn|group=note|These numbers are total, and include non-Hindus from Asia who were expelled, such as [[Sikhism|Sikhs]].<ref name=panayi43/><ref>{{cite book|author1=Pashaura Singh|author2=Louis E. Fenech|title=The Oxford Handbook of Sikh Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7YwNAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA499 |year=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-100411-7|pages=499–500}}</ref>}}), [[India]] (15,000 refugees), [[Canada]] (8,000 refugees), the [[United States]] (1,500 refugees) and in smaller numbers to other countries such as [[Australia]].<ref name="Nyep48"/><ref name=panayi43>{{cite book|author1=P. Panayi|author2=P. Virdee|title=Refugees and the End of Empire: Imperial Collapse and Forced Migration in the Twentieth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8cCHDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA42| year=2011| publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-0-230-30570-0|pages=42–43}}</ref> The expulsion removed most of Uganda's "industrialists, traders, artisans and civil servants", states Christopher Senyonjo, and their properties were re-allocated to civilians and Ugandan Army officials who supported Idi Amin.<ref>{{cite book|author=Christopher Senyonjo|title=In Defense of All God’s Children: The Life and Ministry of Bishop Christopher Senyonjo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nrfxCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT42|year=2016|publisher=Church Publishing|isbn=978-0-8192-3244-1|page=42}}</ref> Uganda faced a shortage of skilled professionals such as doctors, bankers, nurses and teachers. It triggered a financial crisis and a collapse of businesses, including cement and sugar production, causing long-term economic devastation in Uganda.<ref>{{cite book|author=C. Davis|title=Creating Postcolonial Literature: African Writers and British Publishers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VOKIXdIQO9gC&pg=PT56 |year=2013|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-32838-0|page=56}}</ref>
{{clear}}
==Post-Idi Amin conditions== Twenty years after the Idi Amin expulsion, Uganda reversed its laws selectively targeting Hindus and other Indian religions.<ref name="JonesRyan2006p10"/> This policy, offered in cooperation with the [[World Bank]], included a return of properties seized by Idi Amin's government, such as empty and unused factories, back to the families if they returned and recreated employment.<ref name=fick199/>
Hindus are a tiny minority in the total [[Uganda]]n population of about 27 million. The official demographics lists Christians and Muslims separately, but includes Hindus, Jains, Sikhs, Buddhists and traditional African religions as others. Approximately 65% of the South Asians living in Uganda are Hindus.<ref name="JonesRyan2006p10">{{cite book|author1=Constance Jones|author2=James D. Ryan|title=Encyclopedia of Hinduism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OgMmceadQ3gC&pg=PA10 |year=2006|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-7564-5|pages=10–11}}</ref> There is a [[Swaminarayan temple]] in [[Kampala]].<ref>[http://www.baps.org/Global-Network/Africa/Kampala.aspx BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir], BAPS Swaminarayan Sanstha, Africa</ref>
